column137: In some cases there were parts of a symbol that seemed to be critical to the makeup of that symbol - in most cases it was a vertical line that wasn't present in the input. I would also be curious to see how this handled other character sets as there are similarities to utf-8 so the outputs would be interesting to see in that case.  I marked the characters where the input was too far away from the learned symbols to allow the output to be correct in my opinion. The "challenge" here for me as a participant is that I've never seen those symbols in my life so I have no way of knowing if the other symbols could be incorrectly matched - i.e. matching d instead of b.
column220: In some cases the output was too far away from what's expected. However, I can appreciate that a badly written "2" can be mistaken for a 7 if the tail of the 7 is flared out. Those edge cases are interesting as humans such as doctors are notorious for bad handwriting so I'd imagine some level of pattern match and assumption is required to ensure validity of output.

column11: Mozilla/5.0 (Windows NT 10.0; Win64; x64) AppleWebKit/537.36 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/93.0.4577.63 Safari/537.36
column137: Human handwriting is very unique human to human and so the spacing and curves of each symbol can be quite messy. The program did well but some symbols look very similar when written by different people and I think that makes it hard for the program to determine as the computer generated symbols are uniform with the same degree of curvature and roundedness, with regular spacing. Human handwriting is not like this at all and so there are lots of variables from person to person, which i think confuses the program. I also think it wouldn't be reliable as many symbols, numbers and letters look very alike, especially when written by a human, and so I can see a lot of room for mislabelling and incorrect outputs.
column220: Human handwriting is unique and many numbers and letters and symbols can look very similar when written by other people. The characteristics of the numbers can look similar and that is what the program picks up on, like the elongation of some lines or the additional strikethroughs. Though it is these details that the program confuses for other numbers and so what can be determined by the human eye from understanding human handwriting and experience, the computer just can't seem to tell. The program does well but it doesn't quite understand different conventions or styles of writing, which can be affected by writing speed, right or left handedness and other things.
